  	... 16 more
  ```
  
  In a Spring Boot/Spring world, fixing these would require something akin to the following:
  
  ```java
  public class MyRuntimeHints implements RuntimeHintsRegistrar {
      public MyRuntimeHints() {
      }
  
      @Override
      public void registerHints(final RuntimeHints hints, final ClassLoader classLoader) {
          hints.reflection().registerType(java.lang.Module.class, MemberCategory.INVOKE_DECLARED_METHODS);
      }
  }
  ```
  
  ...which in the end generates AOT JSON metadata for reflection as such:
  
  ```json
    {
      "name": "java.lang.Module",
      "allDeclaredMethods": true
    }
  ```
  
  ...and this would have to be repeated for `AntClassLoaderHandler`, and likely many others. 
  
  This JSON metadata is ideally found and provided by the project itself, so the AOT engine can just pick up up what it needs without having each consumer project declare and configure reflection metadata on their own. Alternatively, there is https://github.com/oracle/graalvm-reachability-metadata which allows contributors to push this sort of configuration into a global repository that may be used by AOT engines and appropriate build plugins. 
  
  Before reaching out to graalvm-reachability-metadata, I figured to ask: Is this something classgraph might be open to supporting out of the box, whereby native-image configuration would be maintained and hosted here directly and then released? 
  
  
  
  
  
  --- 756 ---
  GraalVM native image failures during build-time scanning
  This is actually a continuation of #681 which was closed.
  
  I was trying with ClassGraph `4.8.154` and encountered the same issue. I have set the appropriate `--initialize-at-build-time` arguments so that ClassGraph and my class performing the scan are initialized at build time.
  
  I referenced the project on https://github.com/SoftInstigate/classgraph-on-graalvm and found that this particular issue was introduced in `4.8.128`. The last version that worked on that project was `4.8.127`. https://github.com/classgraph/classgraph/compare/classgraph-4.8.127...classgraph-4.8.128.
  
  This particular issue was introduced by the change to add a `ClassMemberCache`. This cache ends up being statically held because `ReflectionUtils` statically stores the `ReflectionDriver`.
  https://github.com/classgraph/classgraph/blob/dc3253595946048d2dbf4ce01e0b6333fa956b33/src/main/java/nonapi/io/github/classgraph/reflection/ReflectionUtils.java#L43
  
  I can get around this issue by setting the `reflectionDriver` to `null` after the scan has completed.
  
  ```java
  nonapi.io.github.classgraph.reflection.ReflectionUtils.reflectionDriver = null;
  ```
  
  In my actual application I encountered another issue with the `CallStackReader` statically storing `callStack`.
  
  https://github.com/classgraph/classgraph/blob/8b358c63db2b4a5dc844f96e9453809b8f83adf8/src/main/java/nonapi/io/github/classgraph/classpath/CallStackReader.java#L45
  
  I had to use reflection to clear this out after the scan has completed for the image building process to complete successfully.
  
  ```java
  try {
  	Class<?> clazz = Class.forName("nonapi.io.github.classgraph.classpath.CallStackReader");
  	Field field = clazz.getDeclaredField("callStack");
  	field.setAccessible(true);
  	field.set(null, null);
  } catch (ClassNotFoundException | NoSuchFieldException | SecurityException | IllegalArgumentException
  		| IllegalAccessException e) {
  	throw new RuntimeException(e);
  }
  ```
  I will try to find time to create a small test case project that demonstrates this.
  
  
  
  
  
  
  --- 860 ---
  Trouble with GraalVM native-image post compile
  Hello,
  
  I'm trying to build a project that uses ClassGraph into a GraalVM native-image.
  
  GraalVM does not handle reflection dynamically, so when code uses reflection, those references have to be explicitly stated in a json file so that Graal can make those connections during the compile phase.
  
  GraalVM also offers a handy tracer option that one can use where it monitors reflection use of your code as you run it and put it through its paces etc. where it automatically builds the necessary json files that you then include in your build statement when you compile the code.
  
  The issue I'm running into seems to be with the way that ClassGraph does things so dynamically. My assumption is that there might be some nested dynamic reflection going on that the tracer tool can't catch and I'm not sure how to locate those so that I can add them into the proper json file.
  
